Ahh this is a very smart question 👀 — you’re thinking like a real developer now.

Short answer:

👉 Yes, it is possible
BUT ❗ not clean with HTTPS + Credential Manager

👉 The correct professional way = use SSH keys (best solution)

🧠 Why your current approach is painful

With HTTPS:

Git stores one credential per domain (github.com) ❌
So it keeps switching / conflicting ❌

That’s why you’re stuck.

✅ BEST SOLUTION → Use SSH for multiple GitHub accounts

👉 This lets you use:

Monolith → Account A
Microservices → Account B

without conflicts

🚀 Step-by-step (don’t worry, I’ll keep it simple)
🔹 Step 1: Generate SSH keys (2 keys)

Open terminal:

👉 For Monolith account
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "monolith-email@example.com"

Save as:

id_ed25519_monolith
👉 For Microservices account
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "microservices-email@example.com"

Save as:

id_ed25519_micro
🔹 Step 2: Add keys to GitHub

Go to GitHub

For each account:
Settings → SSH and GPG keys
Click New SSH key
Paste key:
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_micro.pub
🔹 Step 3: Configure SSH config file

Open:

~/.ssh/config

Add:

# Monolith account
Host github-monolith
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_monolith

# Microservices account
Host github-micro
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_micro
🔹 Step 4: Change remote URL
👉 For microservices project
git remote set-url origin git@github-micro:DeepaShashwathSanath/ShreeBenakaSpace-Microservices.git
👉 For monolith project
git remote set-url origin git@github-monolith:<monolith-username>/<repo>.git
🎯 Result

Now:

Project	GitHub Account
Monolith	Account A ✅
Microservices	Account B ✅

👉 No switching
👉 No credential issues
👉 No 403 errors

